n1. **Failed first attempt**: The June 5 completion already failed by June 12-23. Algae resurfaced within a week; paint began peeling within two weeks.\n\n2. **Cost and scope escalation**: Initial estimate of $1.5M/one week ballooned to $16M total, suggesting either:\n   - Initial estimates were wildly unrealistic, or\n   - Problems were more severe than anticipated\n   - Both suggest poor planning and execution capacity\n\n3. **Contractor disputes**: The selection of contractors and the lawsuit suggest ongoing administrative/legal friction that could delay or complicate repairs.\n\n4. **Root cause uncertain**: The fact that algae returned immediately after the first \"completion\" suggests the underlying cause (water treatment, algae genesis mechanism) wasn't properly addressed. Simply repainting won't solve a biological problem.\n\n5. **Recent mention of hydrogen peroxide treatment** (early July) indicates they're trying a different approach, but no evidence yet of success.\n\n6. **Timeline pressure**: Contractors said \"weeks\" for the second repair attempt (starting ~June 21). \"Weeks\" typically means 2-4 weeks, putting realistic completion around mid-July to early August at best\u2014leaving only 3-4 weeks with \"no further repairs needed\" before September 1.\n\n7. **Institutional credibility issues**: The pattern of failed execution and disputed facts (vandalism vs. natural peeling, \"residual\" algae claims) suggests future setbacks are likely to occur and be publicly reported.\n\n## (g) Community prediction\n\nNo community prediction was provided in the materials, so no divergence comparison is possible.\n\n---\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\n**Why YES is unlikely:**\n\n- The first repair already failed spectacularly (algae back in a week, peeling in ~2 weeks)\n- This suggests either fundamental misdiagnosis or poor execution\n- Only ~61 days remain, and the repairs just restarted ~10 days ago\n- Even if repairs are completed by mid-August, only 2-3 weeks of \"